Snick or snee, snick a snee, or snickersnee ----
obsolete in conversational use, but kept alive by Gilbert and Sullivan's Mikado. And in crossword puzzles.

@Linda Jo @Alex
I'll further clarify that in my experience a SCHMEAR is a lesser amount of spread (I've only ever heard it in reference to cream cheeses on bagels, although I'm seeing citations involving butter and peanut butter and a few other things). Someone dieting or not too hungry might prefer a schmear to a normal serving. [I will note that AI does not agree with this definition, but a  quick survey of Jewish people in the immediate vicinity yielded the phrase "minimal amount of cream cheese".] 

I'm curious if any other SCHMEARers want to ring in with their understanding of the word.

@Bob T.

yes, schmear is minimal to purists. But as bagels have spread out across the country, the definition of schmear has loosened.

I'm not going down the rabbithole of NYC bagels vs. Montreal bagels.

@Linda Jo
Discretion is the bagel part of valour, LJ.
As for the SCHMEAR quantum, I'm wildly on the other side. A SCHMEAR, esp. of butter, is a generous dollop. More than enough to cover each half of your bagel to any reasonably required depth.

@Petrol
I'm an American and I still had trouble with BURN SAGE. While that's technically what you do to purify something, I've never heard anyone actually say BURN SAGE. We say "smudge." I could not for the life of me figure that one out, despite the fact that I have actually done this thing.

I did not care for that corner either.

@Jennifer
